:58**: Condition 3 (large counts) is calculated and verified using $p_0 = 0.5$.\n    *   **05:20**: A concluding statement, \"The conditions are met,\" appears.\n*   **05:28 - 05:31**: A blue transition slide titled \"LET'S PRACTICE\" is shown.\n*   **05:31 - 06:39**: A new \"Checking Conditions\" slide presents a practice problem involving a mayor investigating the proportion of adults whose favorite sport is football. The step-by-step verification appears on screen:\n    *   **06:05**: Condition 1 is checked.\n    *   **06:12**: Condition 2 is checked.\n    *   **06:21**: Condition 3 calculations are shown using $p_0 = 0.4$.\n    *   **06:36**: The conclusion, \"The conditions are met,\" is displayed.\n*   **06:39 - 06:42**: A blue transition slide titled \"WHAT SHOULD WE TAKE AWAY?\" is shown.\n*   **06:42 - 07:26**: The \"Key Takeaways\" slide recaps the lesson by answering the two initial questions:\n    *   At **06:48**, it states to use a \"one-sample z test\".\n    *   Starting at **06:58**, it lists the three necessary conditions to verify (random sample, 10% rule, and large counts).\n*   **07:26 - 08:00**: The final slide displays a simple \"Thank you.\" on a blue background.","numLines":28,"startLine":1,"totalLines":28}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"e70dd990-e9dd-43ff-8f99-8d7fea65db0d"}
{"parentUuid":"d66baa9e-5716-415b-8c13-cd00d5262d0b","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"C:\\Users\\ColsonR\\apstats-live-worksheet","sessionId":"a26dd791-6ed3-408b-a594-2da0ac778535","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"master","slug":"twinkling-giggling-barto","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_018Kfz6TzrmAuw8ZUiHhBJNm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01SrirxmvvYf5TxPTuHgBXkd","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"C:\\Users\\ColsonR\\apstats-live-worksheet\\u6\\apstat_6-4-2_transcription.txt"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":7823,"cache_read_input_tokens":9341,"output_tokens":354,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":7823,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"requestId":"req_011CYjAZ7cJAaRCc4ktiLAsC","type":"assistant","uuid":"4cffed53-12ea-4c3f-a4fb-4d4e99b5ccae","timestamp":"2026-03-05T02:44:32.695Z"}
{"parentUuid":"4cffed53-12ea-4c3f-a4fb-4d4e99b5ccae","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"C:\\Users\\ColsonR\\apstats-live-worksheet","sessionId":"a26dd791-6ed3-408b-a594-2da0ac778535","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"master","slug":"twinkling-giggling-barto","type":"progress","data":{"type":"hook_progress","hookEvent":"PostToolUse","hookName":"PostToolUse:Read","command":"callback"},"parentToolUseID":"toolu_01SrirxmvvYf5TxPTuHgBXkd","toolUseID":"toolu_01SrirxmvvYf5TxPTuHgBXkd","timestamp":"2026-03-05T02:44:32.710Z","uuid":"a9756ea5-84b4-4e8d-9b90-5cf4ed057e79"}
{"parentUuid":"4cffed53-12ea-4c3f-a4fb-4d4e99b5ccae","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"C:\\Users\\ColsonR\\apstats-live-worksheet","sessionId":"a26dd791-6ed3-408b-a594-2da0ac778535","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"master","slug":"twinkling-giggling-barto","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01SrirxmvvYf5TxPTuHgBXkd","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→\n     2→\n     3→\n     4→Here's a transcription of the video, complete with timestamps:\n     5→\n     6→**00:00** Hi, this is Josh Tabor from Canyon del Oro High School in Tucson, Arizona. Here with a video about 6.4, setting up a test for a population proportion. In this video, we'll discuss how to identify the procedure and check the conditions for performing a significance test for a population proportion.\n     7→\n     8→**00:21** Let's start by talking about what we'll learn in this video. First, how do we identify an appropriate significance test procedure for a population proportion? And second, how do we verify the conditions for performing a significance test for a population proportion?\n     9→\n    10→**00:39** Let's start by looking at an example. The example might be familiar if you've watched some of the previous videos. To investigate if high school students associate the color green with being more natural, two student researchers randomly selected 30 students from their school. Each student was asked to taste two cups of lemonade in random order and state which one tasted more natural. One of the cups was green and the other cup was white. Unknown to the taste testers was the fact that both cups contained the same brand of lemonade. Of the 30 students, 18 stated that the lemonade in the green cup tasted more natural.\n    11→\n    12→**01:20** So in the previous video, we learned how to state hypotheses. And just as a reminder, the null is that p equals 0.5. And the alternative is that p is greater than 0.5 where p is the proportion of all students at this school who would choose the green cup.\n    13→\n    14→**01:35** Now as far as identifying the procedure, there's lots of different significance test procedures that you're going to learn this year in unit six, seven, eight, and nine. Some will involve one sample, like the one we're looking at. And others will involve two samples like you'll learn about later in unit six. Some involve proportions, like ours. Others involve means or slopes or distributions or relationships. Again, you'll learn lots of different kinds of significance tests this year in AP statistics.\n    15→\n    16→**02:04** When the goal though is to test a claim about the proportion of successes in a single population, we use a one sample Z test for a population proportion. That probably sounds familiar because earlier in this unit, we learned a one sample Z interval for a population proportion. The names are almost identical except in topic 6.2 and 6.3, we were talking about calculating a confidence interval. In topic 6.4 to 6.7, we're going to be talking about performing a significance test.\n    17→\n    18→**02:37** Now let's talk about checking the conditions. So after identifying the correct procedure, you must verify that the conditions for using that procedure are met. In general, you should always be looking for independence in the methods used to collect the data and that the appropriate sampling distribution has the correct shape. The details of these conditions are going to vary from procedure to procedure, but you're going to see some commonalities as well. In fact, this should sound very familiar from topic 6.2.\n    19→\n    20→**03:08** Now here's the specific conditions we need to check for a one sample Z test for a population proportion. To check for independence, we need to see that the data are collected from a random sample from the population of interest. And when sampling without replacement, the sample size needs to be less than or equal to 10% of the population size.\n    21→\n    22→**03:31** Now to check that the shape of the sampling distribution is approximately normal, we have to check both that N times p sub zero is greater than or equal to 10. And N times one minus p sub zero is greater than or equal to 10 where p sub zero is the proportion specified by the null hypothesis. Note that condition three differs for confidence intervals and significance tests. The first two conditions are exactly the same, but the third condition differs. Remember, when we're doing a significance test, we always start by assuming the null hypothesis is true. So we use that null hypothesis value p sub zero in our check of the conditions. And you'll see later on that we'll use that same value in our standard error.\n    23→\n    24→**04:15** Now for our study, remember the context, they randomly selected 30 students and 18 of the 30 students said that lemonade in the green cup tasted more natural. Also remember that our null hypothesis is p equals 0.5.\n    25→\n    26→**04:30** So our first condition is met. The students were randomly selected. The second condition is that we have to assume that the sample size of 30 is less than or equal to 10% of the total number of students at the school. You'll find this to be the case often where you're not given the specific population size. In that case, you need to make a statement like I did here where we have to make an assumption that this is true. And it's quite reasonable, most high schools are bigger than 300 students. Finally, our third condition is that N times p sub zero or 30 times 0.5 equals 15. That's greater than 10. And then 30 times one minus 0.5 is also 15. That's greater than or equal to 10. Notice we're not using the observed successes and failures from the sample. We're using the expected number of successes and failures if the null hypothesis were true. In this case, all three conditions have been met. So we could proceed to calculations. We'll learn about the calculations in the next video.\n    27→\n    28→**05:28** Now here's a chance for you to practice. A newspaper reports that 40% of adults in the United States would say football is their favorite sport. The mayor of a town wonders if the proportion of adults in the town who would say football is their favorite sport differs from the national proportion. To investigate, the mayor will select a random sample of 100 adults in the town and ask each adult to name his or her favorite sport. Check if the conditions for performing a significance test are met. Go ahead and pause the video and give this a try yourself.\n    29→\n    30→**06:03** Okay, let's see how you did. The first condition is met because the mayor states that the sample will be selected at random. The second condition is also met. If we assume that the sample size of 100 is less than 10% of the total number of adults in the town. And finally, the third condition is met. When we check N times p sub zero, we get 40. And N times one minus p sub zero is 60. Remember, we use the null hypothesis value there. And so both 40 and 60 are at least 10. So the conditions are met in this case.\n    31→\n    32→**06:39** Let's review what you should have learned in this video. First, how do we identify an appropriate significance test procedure for a population proportion? Well, when you're testing a claim about the proportion of successes in a population, we use a one sample Z test for a population proportion. And how do we verify that the conditions for performing the test are met? First, we need to check that the data is collected using a random sample from the population. Second, when sampling without replacement, the sample size is less than or equal to 10% of the population size. And finally, both N times p sub zero and N times one minus p sub zero are at least 10 where p sub zero is the proportion specified by the null hypothesis.\n    33→\n    34→**07:26** This has been Josh Tabor. Thanks for tuning in."}]},"uuid":"ca6a5ba4-c88f-4a75-81a2-e786500080d9","timestamp":"2026-03-05T02:44:32.709Z","toolUseResult":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\Users\\ColsonR\\apstats-live-worksheet\\u6\\apstat_6-4-2_transcription.txt","content":"\n\n\nHere's a transcription of the video, complete with timestamps:\n\n**00:00** Hi, this is Josh Tabor from Canyon del Oro High School in Tucson, Arizona. Here with a video about 6.4, setting up a test for a population proportion. In this video, we'll discuss how to identify the procedure and check the conditions for performing a significance test for a population proportion.\n\n**00:21** Let's start by talking about what we'll learn in this video. First, how do we identify an appropriate significance test procedure for a population proportion? And second, how do we verify the conditions for performing a significance test for a population proportion?\n\n**00:39** Let's start by looking at an example. The example might be familiar if you've watched some of the previous videos. To investigate if high school students associate the color green with being more natural, two student researchers randomly selected 30 students from their school. Each student was asked to taste two cups of lemonade in random order and state which one tasted more natural. One of the cups was green and the other cup was white. Unknown to the taste testers was the fact that both cups contained the same brand of lemonade. Of the 30 students, 18 stated that the lemonade in the green cup tasted more natural.\n\n**01:20** So in the previous video, we learned how to state hypotheses. And just as a reminder, the null is that p equals 0.5. And the alternative is that p is greater than 0.5 where p is the proportion of all students at this school who would choose the green cup.\n\n**01:35** Now as far as identifying the procedure, there's lots of different significance test procedures that you're going to learn this year in unit six, seven, eight, and nine. Some will involve one sample, like the one we're looking at. And others will involve two samples like you'll learn about later in unit six. Some involve proportions, like ours. Others involve means or slopes or distributions or relationships. Again, you'll learn lots of different kinds of significance tests this year in AP statistics.\n\n**02:04** When the goal though is to test a claim about the proportion of successes in a single population, we use a one sample Z test for a population proportion. That probably sounds familiar because earlier in this unit, we learned a one sample Z interval for a population proportion. The names are almost identical except in topic 6.2 and 6.3, we were talking about calculating a confidence interval. In topic 6.4 to 6.7, we're going to be talking about performing a significance test.\n\n**02:37** Now let's talk about checking the conditions. So after identifying the correct procedure, you must verify that the conditions for using that procedure are met. In general, you should always be looking for independence in the methods used to collect the data and that the appropriate sampling distribution has the correct shape. The details of these conditions are going to vary from procedure to procedure, but you're going to see some commonalities as well. In fact, this should sound very familiar from topic 6.2.\n\n**03:08** Now here's the specific conditions we need to check for a one sample Z test for a population proportion. To check for independence, we need to see that the data are collected from a random sample from the population of interest. And when sampling without replacement, the sample size needs to be less than or equal to 10% of the population size.\n\n**03:31** Now to check that the shape of the sampling distribution is approximately normal, we have to check both that N times p sub zero is greater than or equal to 10. And N times one minus p sub zero is greater than or equal to 10 where p sub zero is the proportion specified by the null hypothesis. Note that condition three differs for confidence intervals and significance tests. The first two conditions are exactly the same, but the third condition differs. Remember, when we're doing a significance test, we always start by assuming the null hypothesis is true. So we use that null hypothesis value p sub zero in our check of the conditions. And you'll see later on that we'll use that same value in our standard error.\n\n**04:15** Now for our study, remember the context, they randomly selected 30 students and 18 of the 30 students said that lemonade in the green cup tasted more natural. Also remember that our null hypothesis is p equals 0.5.\n\n**04:30** So our first condition is met. The students were randomly selected. The second condition is that we have to assume that the sample size of 30 is less than or equal to 10% of the total number of students at the school. You'll find this to be the case often where you're not given the specific population size. In that case, you need to make a statement like I did here where we have to make an assumption that this is true. And it's quite reasonable, most high schools are bigger than 300 students. Finally, our third condition is that N times p sub zero or 30 times 0.5 equals 15. That's greater than 10. And then 30 times one minus 0.5 is also 15. That's greater than or equal to 10. Notice we're not using the observed successes and failures from the sample. We're using the expected number of successes and failures if the null hypothesis were true. In this case, all three conditions have been met. So we could proceed to calculations. We'll learn about the calculations in the next video.\n\n**05:28** Now here's a chance for you to practice. A newspaper reports that 40% of adults in the United States would say football is their favorite sport. The mayor of a town wonders if the proportion of adults in the town who would say football is their favorite sport differs from the national proportion. To investigate, the mayor will select a random sample of 100 adults in the town and ask each adult to name his or her favorite sport. Check if the conditions for performing a significance test are met. Go ahead and pause the video and give this a try yourself.\n\n**06:03** Okay, let's see how you did. The first condition is met because the mayor states that the sample will be selected at random. The second condition is also met. If we assume that the sample size of 100 is less than 10% of the total number of adults in the town. And finally, the third condition is met. When we check N times p sub zero, we get 40. And N times one minus p sub zero is 60. Remember, we use the null hypothesis value there. And so both 40 and 60 are at least 10. So the conditions are met in this case.\n\n**06:39** Let's review what you should have learned in this video. First, how do we identify an appropriate significance test procedure for a population proportion? Well, when you're testing a claim about the proportion of successes in a population, we use a one sample Z test for a population proportion. And how do we verify that the conditions for performing the test are met? First, we need to check that the data is collected using a random sample from the population. Second, when sampling without replacement, the sample size is less than or equal to 10% of the population size. And finally, both N times p sub zero and N times one minus p sub zero are at least 10 where p sub zero is the proportion specified by the null hypothesis.\n\n**07:26** This has been Josh Tabor. Thanks for tuning in.","numLines":34,"startLine":1,"totalLines":34}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"4cffed53-12ea-4c3f-a4fb-4d4e99b5ccae"}
